
[1]proxy

   PROX'Y, n. [contracted from procuracy, or some word from the root of
   procure, proctor.]

   1. The agency of another who acts as a substitute for his principal;
   agency of a substitute; appearance of a representative. None can be
   familiar by proxy. None can be virtuous or wise by proxy.

   2. The person who is substituted or deputed to act for another. A wise
   man will not commit important business to a proxy, when he can transact
   it in person. In England, any peer may make another lord of parliament
   his proxy to vote for him in his absence.

   3. In popular use, an election or day of voting for officers of
   government.
